se Democrats are sluggishly coming around to depriving Johnson of votes on =
a partisan bill, a
sentiment echoed by Democratic Leader <strong>Hakeem</strong> <strong>Jeffr=
ies</strong> in a Friday letter to his colleagues: =E2=80=9CRepublicans hav=
e used their control of the House, the Senate, and the presidency to destro=
y the programs taxpayers deserve,=E2=80=9D Jeffries wrote. He went on to sa=
y that House Democrats would =E2=80=9Centhusiastically=E2=80=9D support a b=
ill that protects Social Security and Medicare, but that they =E2=80=9Ccann=
ot back a measure that rips away=E2=80=9D those programs. Medicaid, he adde=
d, =E2=80=9Cis our redline.=E2=80=9D A
Democratic aide offered a more succinct translation: =E2=80=9CIf Johnson ne=
eds the votes, then he needs to fucking talk to Jeffries.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/=
>The funding deadline has been an ongoing preoccupation among House Democra=
ts since they helped Republicans with a three-month funding extension back =
in December=E2=80=94a short-term reprieve that Musk nearly blew up over the=
 number of the pages in the bill, Democrats say. Since then, of course, the=
 party has been furious that Musk and DOGE are slashing government programs=
,
and firing federal workers, without the consent or direction of Congress. M=
ost House Democrats believe that the public will side with them=E2=80=94a f=
air bet, as Republicans are historically more associated with shutdowns. An=
d Musk=E2=80=99s actions give Republicans little credibility with the publi=
c.<br/><br/>But there are still jitters. Not surprisingly, Democrats in vul=
nerable seats, such as Rep. <strong>Jared Golden </strong>of Maine=E2=80=94=
who represents a rural district that Trump won by more than nine percentage
points, and who could face a formidable candidate, former Maine Governor <s=
trong>Paul</strong> <strong>LePage</strong>, in 2026=E2=80=94may see little=
 upside in voting against the Republicans. There are also the old-school in=
stitutionalists, who think a government shutdown is bad under any circumsta=
nces. Some Maryland and Virginia Democrats, who represent the D.C suburbs t=
hat are home to government workers, worry about employees being furloughed,=
 on top of the ongoing chaos and uncertainty of their
jobs. As of this weekend, Democratic leadership was still discussing whethe=
r they=E2=80=99ll whip the vote to keep their members united, or let member=
s be free agents. The caucus will meet on Tuesday morning to discuss.<br/><=
br/>One Democratic strategist told me that internal polling shows that Repu=
blicans will be blamed if the government shutters, but added that what matt=
ers most is the messaging <em>during </em>a shutdown. The public could thin=
k Republicans are so anti-government, as
Musk has proven, that Trump and co. get blamed. Let=E2=80=99s see if that h=
appens.</p></div>
